### ==========================================
### End-to-End Choreography Chain (Lesson 12)
### Order → Payment → Inventory → Notification
### ==========================================
###
### Prerequisites:
###   docker compose up -d      (RabbitMQ + Mongo)
###   Start all four sidecars (see docs/commands.md)
###
### Watch the four terminals — you should see, in order:
###   order-service        : published OrderCreated
###   payment-service      : Received OrderCreated → published PaymentCompleted
###   inventory-service    : Received PaymentCompleted → published InventoryReserved
###   notification-service : Received InventoryReserved → EMAIL SENT, SMS SENT

POST {{orderService}}/orders
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
    "orderId": "ORD-777",
    "amount": 250
}

###
### Verify each service's Mongo collection now has a document
### (orders, payments, inventory).

###

### ==========================================
### Dead Letter Topic (Lesson 14)
### ==========================================
###
### Any orderId starting with "FAIL-" triggers a permanent failure
### inside payment-service. Dapr will:
###
###   1. Deliver OrderCreated to payment-service (attempt 1) → throws
###   2. Retry via `pubsubInboundRetry` policy (attempts 2..4)
###   3. After maxRetries=3, forward the CloudEvent to the
###      `payment-failed` dead letter topic
###   4. payment-service's DLQ subscription logs it (see terminal)
###
### Watch payment-service terminal for the [DLQ] block.

POST {{orderService}}/orders
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
    "orderId": "FAIL-500",
    "amount": 999
}

###

### ==========================================
### Transactional Outbox Chaos Test (Lesson 15)
### ==========================================
###
### The /orders/chaos endpoint calls createOrder() then throws.
### Response is HTTP 500, but the sidecar has already transactionally
### committed both the state save AND the OrderCreated publish.
###
### Expected:
###   - HTTP response       : 500 with "Simulated crash AFTER save..."
###   - Redis (orderstore)  : key `ORD-CHAOS-1` exists
###   - RabbitMQ            : order-created delivered
###   - payment-service     : Received OrderCreated → published PaymentCompleted
###   - inventory + notification: full chain still fires
###
### Before Lesson 15 this would have left an orphaned order with no
### downstream processing.

POST {{orderService}}/orders/chaos
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
    "orderId": "ORD-CHAOS-2",
    "amount": 42
}

###

### ==========================================
### Idempotency (Lesson 16)
### ==========================================
###
### Publish the same CloudEvent id twice directly through the
### order-service sidecar's pub/sub endpoint. Payment-service will
### process the first, then log "[idempotency] skipping duplicate"
### on the second — no double payment, no double inventory reservation,
### no double notification.

@daprPubsub = pubsub
@daprTopic = order-created
@dupEventId = evt-fixed-idempotency-1

POST {{orderDapr}}/v1.0/publish/{{daprPubsub}}/{{daprTopic}}
Content-Type: application/cloudevents+json

{
    "specversion": "1.0",
    "id": "{{dupEventId}}",
    "source": "manual-test",
    "type": "com.dapr.event.sent",
    "datacontenttype": "application/json",
    "data": {
        "orderId": "ORD-DUP-1",
        "amount": 111,
        "status": "CREATED",
        "createdAt": "2026-07-06T12:00:00Z",
        "items": [{"sku": "SKU-DUP", "quantity": 1}]
    }
}

###
### Send the exact same event again — same "id".
### payment-service should log:
###   [idempotency] skipping duplicate order-created eventId=evt-fixed-idempotency-1

POST {{orderDapr}}/v1.0/publish/{{daprPubsub}}/{{daprTopic}}
Content-Type: application/cloudevents+json

{
    "specversion": "1.0",
    "id": "{{dupEventId}}",
    "source": "manual-test",
    "type": "com.dapr.event.sent",
    "datacontenttype": "application/json",
    "data": {
        "orderId": "ORD-DUP-2",
        "amount": 111,
        "status": "CREATED",
        "createdAt": "2026-07-06T12:00:00Z",
        "items": [{"sku": "SKU-DUP", "quantity": 1}]
    }
}

###

### ==========================================
### Dapr Workflow (Lesson 17)
### ==========================================
###
### Kicks off the orchestrated version of the order saga.
### Response gives you an `instanceId` — plug it into the GET below
### to observe status. Behind the scenes, order-service's
### WorkflowRuntime calls three activities in sequence via
### Dapr Service Invocation:
###
###   OrderSagaWorkflow
###     ├── processPaymentActivity      → payment-service /payments
###     ├── reserveInventoryActivity    → inventory-service /inventory/reserve
###     └── sendNotificationActivity    → notification-service /notifications/send
###
### Compare to the choreography version (POST /orders) — same 4-service
### chain, but every step is now durable and centrally observable.

POST {{orderService}}/orders/workflow
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
    "orderId": "ORD-WF-2",
    "amount": 999
}

###

### Poll status. Copy the instanceId from the response above.

@wfInstance = 11c825a0-fd56-433b-bf59-05d5cb6b9613
GET {{orderService}}/orders/workflow/{{wfInstance}}

###

### Cancel a running workflow (useful if it's stuck).

DELETE {{orderService}}/orders/workflow/{{wfInstance}}


###

### ==========================================
### Distributed Lock + Stock (Lesson 18)
### ==========================================

@invSvc = http://localhost:3002

### 1) Seed stock: 3 units of SKU-DEMO

POST {{invSvc}}/inventory/stock/SKU-DEMO
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "quantity": 3
}

### 2) Read stock

GET {{invSvc}}/inventory/stock/SKU-DEMO

### 3) Reserve 2 units — succeeds, stock → 1

POST {{invSvc}}/inventory/reserve
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "paymentId": "pay-lock-1",
    "orderId":  "ord-lock-1",
    "amount":   100,
    "status":   "COMPLETED",
    "processedAt": "2026-07-23T00:00:00Z",
    "items": [ { "sku": "SKU-DEMO", "quantity": 2 } ]
}

### 4) Reserve 2 more — should FAIL with 409 (only 1 left)

POST {{invSvc}}/inventory/reserve
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "paymentId": "pay-lock-2",
    "orderId":  "ord-lock-2",
    "amount":   100,
    "status":   "COMPLETED",
    "processedAt": "2026-07-23T00:00:00Z",
    "items": [ { "sku": "SKU-DEMO", "quantity": 2 } ]
}

### 5) Concurrency proof — jq-only pipeline, no temp files.
### After re-seeding stock to 3, expect exactly 3 × HTTP 200 and 2 × 409.
### Without the lock, all five would succeed and stock would go negative.
###
###   seq 5 | while read i; do
###     (
###       resp=$(curl -sS -o /dev/stdout -w '\n%{http_code}' -X POST http://localhost:3002/inventory/reserve \
###         -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
###         -d "{\"paymentId\":\"c-$i\",\"orderId\":\"c-$i\",\"amount\":1,
###              \"status\":\"COMPLETED\",\"processedAt\":\"2026-07-23T00:00:00Z\",
###              \"items\":[{\"sku\":\"SKU-DEMO\",\"quantity\":1}]}")
###       code=${resp##*$'\n'}
###       body=${resp%$'\n'*}
###       jq -cn --argjson req "$i" --argjson code "$code" --arg body "$body" \
###         '{req:$req, code:$code, body: ($body | try fromjson catch $body)}'
###     ) &
###   done; wait | jq -s '
###     sort_by(.req) as $all
###     | { results: $all,
###         summary: {
###           "200":   [$all[] | select(.code==200)] | length,
###           "409":   [$all[] | select(.code==409)] | length,
###           "other": [$all[] | select(.code!=200 and .code!=409)] | length
###         }
###       }'
